messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /printshops/requests/{id}

All HTTP methods acceptable?
- no

Acceptable HTTP methods (based on the code)
- HEAD: no
- POST: yes
- OPTIONS: no
- TRACE: no
- GET: yes
- PUT: no
- DELETE: no
- PATCH: no

Explanation
- There is no class-level @RequestMapping, so the controller methods use the paths exactly as declared.
- changeStatusPrintShopRequests is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/requests/{id}", method = RequestMethod.POST) — so POST is explicitly accepted for that handler.
- The same path is also mapped to a different handler getPrintShopRequest with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/requests/{id}", method = RequestMethod.GET) — so GET is explicitly accepted on that path (handled by a different controller method).
- No @RequestMapping for this path omits the method attribute (which would have meant "all methods"), and there are no explicit mappings for HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PUT, DELETE or PATCH in the provided source, so those methods are not accepted according to the code. (Per your instruction, I did not assume framework-provided automatic handlers such as automatic HEAD/OPTIONS handling.)
